     <p><strong><p><strong>Don Garrett (ed.), <em>Mary Shepherd’s An Essay upon the Relation of Cause and Effect</em>, Oxford University Press, 2024, 176pp., $29.95 (pbk) ISBN 9780197649633.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Samuel C. Rickless, University of California San Diego</strong></p>
     <p>In his <em>Memoirs of 1879</em>, the well-read philosopher and radical Robert Blakey, who had published a four-volume <em>History of the Philosophy of Mind</em> in 1848, described Mary Shepherd (1777-1847) thus: “She was, without exception, the most eloquent female talker I ever met with. Her lengthened sentences, uttered with great distinction, were quite stunning, and filled one with amazement at the subtility of her mind” (Blakey 1879, 159). Shepherd was not only a stunningly eloquent talker but also an author of stunning philosophical acumen and ambition.</p> <p>Don Garrett’s book is a modern edition of Mary Shepherd’s “An Essay upon the Relation of Cause and Effect” (1824), to which are appended two essays of hers that appeared in 1828, “Observations by Lady Mary Shepherd on [John Fearn’s] the ‘First...
